description: "The chemical reactions and pathways involving organonitrogen compound." [GOC:pr, GOC:TermGenie]
name: organonitrogen compound metabolic process

description: "The chemical reactions and pathways involving a protein. Includes protein modification." [GOC:ma]
name: protein metabolic process

description: "Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of a biological process. Biological processes are regulated by many means; examples include the control of gene expression, protein modification or interaction with a protein or substrate molecule." [GOC:jid]
name: positive regulation of biological process

description: "The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of organonitrogen compound." [GOC:pr, GOC:TermGenie]
name: organonitrogen compound biosynthetic process

description: "A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of an organelle within a cell. An organelle is an organized structure of distinctive morphology and function. Includes the nucleus, mitochondria, plastids, vacuoles, vesicles, ribosomes and the cytoskeleton. Excludes the plasma membrane." [GOC:mah]
name: organelle organization

description: "The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of organic and inorganic nitrogenous compounds." [GOC:jl, ISBN:0198506732]
name: cellular nitrogen compound biosynthetic process

description: "Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of a cellular process, any of those that are carried out at the cellular level, but are not necessarily restricted to a single cell. For example, cell communication occurs among more than one cell, but occurs at the cellular level." [GOC:jid]
name: positive regulation of cellular process

description: "Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a disturbance in organismal or cellular homeostasis, usually, but not necessarily, exogenous (e.g. temperature, humidity, ionizing radiation)." [GOC:mah]
name: response to stress

description: "Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus indicating the organism is under stress. The stress is usually, but not necessarily, exogenous (e.g. temperature, humidity, ionizing radiation)." [GOC:mah]
name: cellular response to stress

description: "The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of substances, including the breakdown of carbon compounds with the liberation of energy for use by the cell or organism." [ISBN:0198547684]
name: catabolic process
